message: The previous player hinted that the vial and filter do not work well together, and my experience confirms this; avoid using both on the same item. Generally, combining two ingredients will result in a negative value. Try applying *one* tool to a newly combined, negative-value item. The 'vial' often turned negative blends into positive, sometimes high-value, extracts, especially with a mix of magical and mundane features. The 'filter' can also yield positive results, particularly when combining two magical ingredients. message: Start by using the 'vial' tool on single, solid ingredients. This reliably creates positive-valued extracts. Combining two 'liquid, extracted, mundane' items further boosts their value significantly. Avoid using the 'filter' tool as it consistently reduces value and adds 'botched filtering' features. message: Hello! For a quick 100 score, look for a 'magical solid' and a 'mundane solid' in your starting ingredients. Combine these two items first (the result will be negative). Then, immediately use the 'vial' tool on this combined item. This strategy consistently yielded a score of 100 for me. Avoid using the 'vial' on magical items or the 'filter' on solid items, as these lead to negative values. Once you have a 30-value mundane liquid and a 30-value magical liquid, combine them for 100 points. Do not combine more than two liquids, as this can also lead to negative values.

message: Focus on using tools correctly! The 'vial' works well on *solids* (both magical and mundane) to create positive-value liquid extracts. The 'filter' works well on *mundane liquids* to create positive-value filtered liquids. Avoid using the 'filter' on solids, especially magical ones, as this often results in negative 'botched' items. When combining, pair processed items that share the same 'mundane' magical property to significantly increase value. Combining processed items with different magical properties (mundane + magical) generally decreases value. Never use tools on items that already have a 'botched' feature, as this further reduces their value.
